		<h2> HTML Tutorial 1: Tags</h2>
			<p>HTML tags are the "hidden" code words behind a web page that defines how your website works, formats and displays the content. Most of
			the tags consist of a two parts - an opening and closing part. They are called <em>&quot;container tags&quot;</em> and begin with a <code>
				 &quot;<&quot; </code> character and end with a <code> &quot;>&quot; </code> character. Between them is the tag name. For example <code>
					  &lt;html&gt; and &lt;/html&gt;</code>. There are some exceptions though, that do not need to be in pairs like the <code> &lt;br /&gt;
							 and &lt;hr /&gt; </code>. <p> There are some other tags, called <em>&quot;inline-tags&quot;</em> which can nest inside the container
								  tags. These are mostly used for text format, adding multimedia and others. HTML tags are essential in orderd if you want your page
									to display properly. You can use as many tags as you want, but with that said, don't overuse them with no purpose. Below is a
									table with the most common tags, every beginner should start with. </p>
	<img class="tags" src="tags.png" alt="HTML Tags Example">
	<hr class="separator">
		<h2> HTML Tutorial 2: Attributes </h2>
			<p>Most HTML tags can have what are called <em>attributes</em>. An attribute defines a property for an element, consists of an attribute / value pair,
				 and appears within the element's start tag. We can look at it as something like a blueprints for the browser. This is an example how it
				 looks like <code> &lt;tag attribute=&quot;value&quot;&gt;Pizza&lt;/tag&gt;</code>. The attribute value is the data you enter for the attribute. </p>
	<img class="attributes" src="attributes.png" alt="HTML Attributes Example">
	<hr class="separator">
		<h2> HTML Tutorial 3: Special characters </h2>
			<p>Special characters in HTML are typically those that can't be easily typed into a keyboard or may cause display issues if typed or pasted
				into a web page. They are usually reserved characters in HTML language or just missing from the keyboard. You can create these characters by
				 starting with an ampersand <code>&quot;&&quot;</code>, followed by a few letters, and ending with a semicolon <code>&quot;;&quot;</code>.
			 For instance, if you want to use quotation marks, which are reservered from the HTML language, you will have to type the entity <code>
			 "&quоt;"</code>. All special characters are case sensitive, so you must be careful with that. <p>There are hundreds of them and it's better
		 just to have them written somewhere rather than trying to remember them, but nevertheless, here is a small part of the most famous of them,
		 just for an example. </p>
